@JonasT `pytz`'s `localize` does something different and something that is *not* supported by `dateutil`. If you read my link you will see why using `pytz` at all is probably a mistake.

If people want to support both `pytz` and `dateutil.tz`, they can use:

```python
def localize(dt, tz):
    if hasattr(tz, 'localize'):
        return tz.localize(dt)
    else:
        return dt.replace(tzinfo=tz)
```

Though frankly I think it's usually unnecessary to actively support `pytz` in this way.

I managed to test this, and it turns out that this is actually a bug upstream in Python 2.7. `_winreg` does not properly know how to handle unicode strings for their keys, as it tries to convert them to ANSI on a call to `OpenKey`.

Apparently there's a package for this [`winreg_unicode`](https://pypi.python.org/pypi/winreg_unicode), but I don't think it's worth adding in another dependency.

@labrys I'm going to merge this PR anyway, but I'm going to open a new issue to leave open to see if there's a way to fix this.

